# REM — Cursor Rules
# These rules guide Cursor AI when working in this repository.

## Project Structure
- `go-api/`        — Go 1.24 REST API (Fiber v2)
- `python-worker/` — FastAPI + Celery async worker
- `dashboard/`     — Next.js 14 dashboard (TypeScript, Tailwind)
- `sdk/python/`    — Python SDK (`rem_memory`)
- `scripts/`       — DB init / seed scripts
- `docs/`          — Documentation

## Go API Rules
- Package name for handlers: `handlers` (inside `internal/api/handlers/`)
- Package name for middleware: `middleware`
- Always use `*zap.Logger` for structured logging, never `fmt.Println`
- Return errors with `handlers.jsonError(c, status, message)`
- All new routes must be registered in `internal/api/router.go`
- Use `deps *handlers.Dependencies` for dependency injection — no global state
- Services live in `internal/services/`; DB clients in `internal/db/<engine>/`

## Python Worker Rules
- All async tasks: Celery in `workers/tasks.py`, call service methods from `services/`
- LLM calls go through `services/llm_service.py` — never call OpenAI directly in handlers
- Consolidation pipeline: `clusterer.py` → `compressor.py`
- Use `httpx.AsyncClient` for external HTTP calls; always set a timeout

## Dashboard Rules
- All pages are under `src/app/dashboard/` and are `"use client"` where state is needed
- CSS custom properties (defined in `globals.css`) must be used for all colours — no hardcoded hex
- Tailwind utility classes are for layout/spacing only; colours come from CSS vars
- Hooks live in `src/lib/hooks/`; shared types in `src/lib/types.ts`
- Components are organised by domain: `ui/`, `landing/`, `dashboard/`, `episodes/`, `graph/`, `semantic/`, `playground/`

## SDK Rules
- Public API surface lives in `rem_memory/client.py`
- All types in `rem_memory/types.py`; keep them in sync with Go domain types
- Integrations (LangChain, AutoGen) are thin adapters — no business logic
- Everything exported from `rem_memory/__init__.py`

## General
- No secrets in source code; use `.env` / environment variables
- All environment variable names are documented in `.env.example`
- Prefer explicit imports over wildcard imports
